data.content:
# Migrating `BackgroundProcessor` to .NET 8

## Critical Breaking Changes

1. **`Thread.Abort()` throws `PlatformNotSupportedException`** — removed entirely in .NET 5+
2. **`Thread.ResetAbort()` also throws** — no longer exists
3. **`ThreadAbortException` is never raised** by the runtime

## The Core Problem

Your `Stop()` relies on `Thread.Abort()` to force-kill a blocked thread. In .NET 8, this is a **runtime exception at the call site**, not on the target thread. You need cooperative cancellation via `CancellationToken`.

## Migrated Code

```csharp
public class BackgroundProcessor : IDisposable
{
    private Task? _workerTask;
    private CancellationTokenSource? _cts;

    public void Start()
    {
        _cts = new CancellationTokenSource();
        var token = _cts.Token;
        _workerTask = Task.Run(() => ProcessLoop(token), token);
    }

    private void ProcessLoop(CancellationToken token)
    {
        while (!token.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            try
            {
                // Pass the token so blocking calls become cancellable
                var item = GetNextItem(token);
                ProcessItem(item);
            }
            catch (OperationCanceledException) when (token.IsCancellationRequested)
            {
                // Graceful shutdown requested — roll back partial work
                RollbackCurrentTransaction();
                break; // exit the loop cleanly
            }
            finally
            {
                FlushBuffers();
            }
        }
    }

    public async Task StopAsync(TimeSpan? timeout = null)
    {
        if (_cts is null || _workerTask is null)
            return;

        _cts.Cancel(); // signal cancellation

        // Wait with a timeout instead of Thread.Sleep + Abort
        var effectiveTimeout = timeout ?? TimeSpan.FromSeconds(5);
        if (await Task.WhenAny(_workerTask, Task.Delay(effectiveTimeout)) != _workerTask)
        {
            // Worker didn't stop in time — log it; you cannot force-kill
            Log.Warning("Worker did not shut down within timeout");
        }
    }

    public void Dispose()
    {
        _cts?.Cancel();
        _workerTask?.Wait(TimeSpan.FromSeconds(2));
        _cts?.Dispose();
    }
}
```

## Key Pitfalls

| Pitfall | Detail |
|---|---|
| **Blocking calls ignore cancellation** | If `GetNextItem()` blocks on a socket/DB call that doesn't accept a `CancellationToken`, cancellation hangs. You **must** thread the token into all I/O. |
| **No force-kill equivalent** | .NET 8 has no safe way to abort a thread. If code truly hangs, your only option is `Environment.FailFast()` or process-level isolation. |
| **`catch (ThreadAbortException)` silently disappears** | The old catch block simply never fires — partial work is **never rolled back** unless you replace it with `OperationCanceledException`. Easy to miss. |
| **`Thread.ResetAbort()` crashes at runtime** | It compiles fine (the API exists) but throws `PlatformNotSupportedException`. CI won't catch this without tests. |
| **`volatile bool` is insufficient** | A volatile flag can't unblock a thread stuck in `Thread.Sleep`, `WaitHandle.WaitOne`, or synchronous I/O. `CancellationToken` integrates with all of these. |

## What to change in `GetNextItem`

```csharp
// BEFORE (.NET Framework) — blocks indefinitely
private WorkItem GetNextItem()
{
    return _queue.Take(); // no way to cancel
}

// AFTER (.NET 8) — cancellable
private WorkItem GetNextItem(CancellationToken token)
{
    return _queue.Take(token); // throws OperationCanceledException
}
```

## If you can't modify blocking calls

As a last resort, run untrusted/unmodifiable blocking code in a **separate process** and kill the process on timeout — this is the only safe force-stop mechanism in .NET 8.
